metadata.name: Happy #90
metadata.description:
Impressions of happiness, generated with code.  Press [P] to animate/pause.

Paint strokes are generated in 3D using three.js. You can drag the mouse to explore different views of the same painting. Interactions require a GPU.
Keyboard controls:
[S] Save the current view.
[P] Play / Pause animation.
[F] Fill the screen.
[1] Save 9:16 image, 3375 x 6000px.
[2] Save 3:4 image, 3000 x 4000px.
[3] Save 1:1 square image, 4000 x 4000px. 
[4] Save 16:9 image, 6000 x 3375px.

Elsif, 2022.04

metadata.name: Brosser #249
metadata.description:
Exploring generative brush strokes to simulate real life paintings. 

- A selection of 19 different palettes
- 4 different drawing styles
- Randomized "color swap" between the primary and secondary colors in each palette

Several other factors determine the output of a piece, including angles, depth, brush length, and brush weight, among others.

metadata.name: Plottable Era: (I) Primitive #195
metadata.description:
'Plottable Era: (I) Primitive' is the first generator in the "Era" generators series, highlighting different periods and civilizations. This first series "Primitive" shows the beginning of mankind with people exploring the mountains and traveling on the sea during sunset.

The digital version simulates ink effects and adds a subtle animation over the water. Each outcome is also physically plottable with pens: A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the piece physically. The plots are designed to be executed in A4 format on either fountain pens (on white paper) or gel pens (Black / Blue).

Thanks to the utility token decoupling, you can get a physical version: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

More details and Source code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-era-primitive

@greweb ‚Äì 2022 ‚Äì tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM ‚Äì CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

reserve is set to previous 2022 physical plot collectors.

metadata.name: CLWBG / #N #40
metadata.description:
Hello guys, this piece is my genesis here at fxhash,250 randomly generated unique pieces.

I like to mix geometric elements with digital cutouts and lots of contrast in my artwork. Generating a composition of colors and elements that even randomly can create harmony between them was my great challenge.

metadata.name: Intangible #6
metadata.description:
Let me take you places. Those are not in your town, not even on your planet. They‚Äôre placed somewhere between reality and subconsciousness.
Enormous, peculiar structures emerge upon you, refusing to be ignored. They are your unfulfilled cravings or ever-lurking demons. They were always there, under your skin, intangible, now they‚Äôve materialized.
You may not like them, they may seem too vast, too scary to tame. But ultimately, you have to face them, unless you enjoy living in their shadow.¬†

___
Inspirations

I‚Äôve never truly realized that, but ever since I remember, the sight of gigantic objects or creatures evoked strong emotions within me.
It probably started with playing Shadow of Colossus (a video game) as a kid and seeing The Cathedral (short movie by Tomasz Bagi≈Ñski). Years later, reading Solaris (by Stanis≈Çaw Lem) aroused the same feeling (among others) of being mesmerized by the vastness. More recently, movies like Denis Villeneuve‚Äôs Arrival (which also nudged my attraction to mystery) and Dune - have charmed me.

Earlier this year I have stumbled across Dawid Planeta (artist and yoga teacher) and began contemplating his visions of mini people in the jungle inhabited by giant animals. These works in particular, plus Hollow - generative series by Jacek Markusiewicz - were probably my final inspirations to make Intangible look the way it does.

Settling semi-random generative structures in some kind of reality, gave them a meaning - they may symbolize things much bigger than you - the ones you try to escape from or those you‚Äôve been longing to experience for years. I have mine, don‚Äôt you?

___
Controls in live mode


Keyboard
[ space ] - toggle light animation
[ S ] - save image with current size (default is 120% of browser window‚Äôs height; you may change browser‚Äôs scale or check URL size param)
[ F ] - fullscreen¬†
[ up / down ] - light intensity
[ left / right ] - base light position
[ 1..5 ] - aspect ratio: 10:16 (‚Äûzero‚Äù ratio), 1:1.4142 (vertical A4), 1:1, 1.4142 (horizontal A4), 16:10
[ B ] - toggle border
[ Z ] - toggle canvas ‚Äûraw‚Äù mode - no shadow / margin (auto applied in fullscreen mode)
[ N ] - toggle ‚Äûthat thing you may not want on print‚Äù


URL params
You may add any number of parameters to the URL to start it with particular settings.‚Ä®
[ animate ] (1/0) - toggle light animation
[ size] (number) - number of px for longer edge, i.e. 4000
[ ratio ] (number or ratio with format: 10/16, 10:16, 10_16) - aspect ratio
[ light ] (number 40..120, some palettes have slightly different limits for good results) - light intensity
[ lightShift] (number -100..100) - base light position
[ border ] (1/0) - toggle border
[ hddcy ] (0/1)

Example: [ &size=4000&border=1&light=100&animate=1 ]¬†


Mobile
[hold 2 fingers for 2s] - save
[double tap] - fullscreen


___
Note:
I encourage you to do some light adjustments before you save an image for print. I‚Äôm pretty sure you can do better than fxrand().


___
Special thanks to my brother Krzycho, for lots of advices / heathy criticism and to Olga, for never-ending excitement and ‚Äûdorady‚Äù.

___
Developed in Javascript, using p5.js (2D Canvas) and chroma.js.

metadata.name: Gradient Ascent #84
metadata.description:
Generates a lo-fi sci-fi landscape and applies effects to the result. Most are 2:3 portrait aspect ratio with a smaller chance for landscape or square.

Several cool bonus features are included. Click to draw the image without post processing which can also be downloaded. The unique effect for each iteration can be applied to any image, just drag and drop! There are also URL commands included for advanced users.

Controls

Click = Toggle Processing
Drag & Drop = Process an Image
1 = Toggle processing
2 = Increase resolution
3 = Save as a png

URL Commands

width and height = Change the output size
hd = Set to 1 to show HD by default

Programmed in Vanilla JavaScript by KilledByAPixel
Code and Outputs are Copyright (C) 2022 Frank Force
Artwork is released under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Obscured by Clouds #94
metadata.description:
This artwork is an attempt to create a painterly texture and to keep the focus on just the paint rather than any object it fills. It's coded in p5.js and uses overlapping translucent shapes to create the texture.

Best viewed on a screen bigger than a mobile phone, while listening to this track called 'Obscured by Clouds' by Pink Floyd: https://open.spotify.com/track/3c8LKbUsjW9lMYQzVScXQT
Press 's' to save the image

Credits:
 - Technique is inspired by this essay by Tyler Hobbs: https://tylerxhobbs.com/essays/2020/how-to-hack-a-painting
 - The name of the artwork is a tribute to my favourite band

metadata.name: Plottable Field (8 frames) #114
metadata.description:
'Field' explores the realm of noise field distortions through many different primitives: 15 unique distributions, 16 possible inks, and many kinds of distortions, ink combinations, and animations,...

A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the 8 frames of this animation on a A4 paper. This is a "plot loop". The physical piece is displayed as aesthetics 4x2 grid of the frames.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulates ink effects. But also, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their materials and ship to collectors ‚Äì as long as NFT is owned at request time.

metadata.name: Tangled #96
metadata.description:
"Tangled" is a generative art project that explores the emergent behaviour of simple shapes moving according to a random flow field. While the final result is always constrained to the shape of a circle, the variation within is endless.

Instructions:
Press "p" to pause the animation.
In live mode, press 1 through 5 to save a PNG version of the final result. The following resolutions are available:
1: 400 x 400 (ideal for Twitter PFP)
2: 1000 x 1000
3: 2000 x 2000
4: 4000 x 4000
5: 5000 x 5000
Please be patient, generating the PNG may take some time!

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Reading a book #520
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.
